<div class="recipe">
<p>You may know these as simply a Viatnamese Sub, which typically consists of lots of fresh or pickled veggies, an intensely flavoured, often spicy meat, placed within a baguette. If you are out shopping and see something labelled as banh mi bread, don't be fooled. Banh mi "bread" really is just a baguette, which comes from the French ties within Viatnam.</p>
<p>These are quickly becoming one of the most popular takeout items recently, and for good reason. But in around 30 minutes of easy work, you can make your homemade version.</p>
<p>Our weeknight variation of the banh mi seeks to simplify the meat, which actually uses ground beef. This is far from traditional, but in this case, it makes for a fine substitute. We will cook the meat in a sauce that will give it a lot of deep flavour, too.</p>
<p>This recipe calls for picked carrots and radishes. While optional, the pickled veggies are very easy to make and are highly recommended. The pickles can be prepared overnight and will stay fresh in an airtight container in the fridge for up to a week. If you don't have the time to prepare these in advance, using them raw will be fine.</p>
<br>
